---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import TableOfContents from '../../components/ui/TableOfContents';
import MethodologyCard from '../../components/ui/MethodologyCard.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "datePublished": "2026-07-13",
  "dateModified": "2026-07-13",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How do I apply thermal paste correctly?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "For standard CPUs, apply a pea-sized dot directly in the center of the CPU metal lid. For larger CPUs (like Intel LGA1700 or AMD AM5), apply a small cross pattern or five small dots (one in each corner, one in the center) to ensure complete spread under cooler pressure."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can static electricity kill PC components?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "While modern components have built-in electrostatic discharge (ESD) protection, it is still possible to damage them. Avoid assembling on carpets, touch a grounded metal object (like a plugged-in PSU chassis) frequently, or wear an anti-static wristband."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<Layout
  title="PC Building Tips: Best Practices & Pitfalls — PSUCheck"
  description="Common PC building mistakes and expert tips. Learn about standoff checks, cable routing shortcuts, thermal paste application, and POST checks."
  schema={faqSchema}
>
  <article class="guide-article">
    <div class="container">
      <header class="guide-header">
        <div class="guide-meta">
          <a href="/methodology" class="badge badge-safe" style="text-decoration:none;">✓ Sizing Methodology Verified</a>
          <span>Updated: July 13, 2026</span>
          <span style="margin: 0 0.5rem; opacity: 0.5;">•</span>
          <span>2 min read</span>
        </div>
        <h1>PC Building Tips: Best Practices &amp; Pitfalls</h1>
        <p class="guide-lead">
          Save yourself hours of troubleshooting. Here are the crucial building tips and common mistakes
          that first-time and veteran builders wish they remembered.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="guide-layout">
        <main class="guide-content" id="main-content">
          <h2>1. Pre-Assembly POST Check (Out-of-Box Test)</h2>
          <p>
            Do not install everything in the case first. Assemble the CPU, cooler, RAM, and GPU on top
            of the motherboard box, plug in power, and bridge the power switch pins with a screwdriver.
            Verifying that your system boots to BIOS *before* mounting it in the case saves massive teardown time if a component is DOA (Dead On Arrival).
          </p>

          <h2>2. Motherboard Standoff Verification</h2>
          <p>
            PC cases use brass standoffs to elevate the motherboard circuit board away from the metal case tray.
            <strong>Never mount a motherboard directly to the case sheet metal without standoffs</strong> — doing so will immediately short out the motherboard, destroying it. Ensure standoffs align *only* with the mounting holes of your motherboard form factor; extra standoffs positioned in the wrong spot can contact circuits on the back of the board, causing shorts.
          </p>

          <h2>3. The Thermal Paste "Pea-Size" Rule</h2>
          <p>
            Too little thermal paste leaves air pockets, causing thermal throttling. Too much paste overflows
            the CPU socket. A single pea-sized drop (about 5-6mm diameter) in the center is perfect for most
            CPUs.
          </p>
          <div class="important-warning">
            <strong>⚠ Warning:</strong> Don't forget to peel off the plastic protective film on the bottom
            of your CPU cooler block before mounting. Leaving this on is one of the most common thermal mistakes.
          </div>

          <h2>4. RAM Channel Optimization</h2>
          <p>
            Almost all modern motherboards prefer RAM to be installed in slots 2 and 4 (counting outwards from the CPU socket).
            Installing RAM in adjacent slots (slots 1 and 2) runs memory in single-channel mode, which severely limits CPU memory bandwidth and lowers gaming framerates by up to 15%.
          </p>

          <h2>5. PSU Cable Routing Discipline</h2>
          <ul>
            <li>Pass cables through case routing grommets *before* screwing down the motherboard if clearances are tight (especially top CPU 8-pin power cables).</li>
            <li>Connect all cable tails to modular power supplies before mounting the PSU inside the basement.</li>
            <li>Do not bundle cables too tightly behind the motherboard tray until you've successfully verified the system boots.</li>
          </ul>

          <div style="margin-top:3rem;display:flex;flex-wrap:wrap;gap:0.75rem;">
            <a href="/pc-builder" class="btn btn-primary">Start planning your custom build</a>
            <a href="/build-plan" class="btn btn-secondary">Generate build blueprint</a>
          </div>
        </main>

        <aside class="guide-sidebar">
          <TableOfContents client:load />
          <MethodologyCard />
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Calculators</h3>
            <ul style="list-style:none;padding:0;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.5rem;font-size:0.875rem;">
              <li><a href="/psu-calculator">⚡ PSU Calculator</a></li>
              <li><a href="/pc-builder">🖥️ PC Build Cost Calculator</a></li>
              <li><a href="/build-plan">📋 Build Blueprint Generator</a></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Other Guides</h3>
            <ul style="list-style:none;padding:0;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.5rem;font-size:0.875rem;">
              <li><a href="/guides/how-to-build-a-pc">How to Build a PC</a></li>
              <li><a href="/guides/atx-3-1-guide">ATX 3.1 Guide</a></li>
              <li><a href="/guides/psu-sizing-guide">PSU Sizing Guide</a></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>

<style>
.guide-article { padding: 4rem 0; }
.guide-header { margin-bottom: 3rem; }
.guide-meta { display:flex; gap: 1rem; align-items:center; font-size: 0.8125rem; color: var(--text-tertiary); margin-bottom: 0.75rem; }
.guide-lead { font-size: 1.15rem; color: var(--text-secondary); max-width: 65ch; line-height: 1.65; margin-top: 0.5rem; }
.guide-layout { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 3rem; }
@media (min-width: 1024px) {
  .guide-layout { grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 8fr) minmax(0, 4fr); }
}
.guide-content h2 { margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
.guide-content p, .guide-content li { color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.75; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
.guide-content ul { padding-left: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
.important-warning { background: var(--status-danger-bg); border-left: 4px solid var(--status-danger); padding: 1rem; border-radius: var(--radius-md); margin-top: 1rem; color: var(--text-secondary); }
.guide-sidebar { display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap: 1.5rem; }
.guide-sidebar .card { padding: 1.25rem; }
</style>
